ia\nBULLET::::- Grand Duke Constantine Pavlovich of Russia\nBULLET::::- Constantine Dragaš\nBULLET::::- Constantine I of Georgia\nBULLET::::- Constantine II of Georgia\nBULLET::::- Constantine I of Imereti\nBULLET::::- Constantine Mavrocordatos\nBULLET::::- Constantine Ypsilantis\nBULLET::::- Tiberius II Constantine\nBULLET::::- Constantine (Briton), king in sub-Roman Britain\nBULLET::::- Constantine of Strathclyde, supposed king of Strathclyde\n\nBULLET::::- Patriarch Constantine I of Constantinople\nBULLET::::- Patriarch Constantine II of Constantinople\nBULLET::::- Patriarch Constantine III of Constantinople\nBULLET::::- Patriarch Constantine IV of Constantinople\nBULLET::::- Patriarch Constantine V of Constantinople\nBULLET::::- Patriarch Constantine VI of Constantinople\nBULLET::::- Pope Constantine\nBULLET::::- Antipope Constantine II\n\nBULLET::::- Constantine-Silvanus (also called Silvanus), founder of the Paulicians\nBULLET::::- Saint Cyril the Philosopher, whose original name was Constantine\nBULLET::::- Constantine the Jew (d. c. 886), Byzantine monk\nBULLET::::- Constantine or Causantín, Earl of Fife (fl. 1095–1128), a Scottish nobleman\nBULLET::::- Constantine the African (c. 1020–1087), a Tunisian doctor\nBULLET::::- Constantine Stilbes (fl. 1070–1220), a Byzantine clergyman and poet\nBULLET::::- Constantine of Preslav, a medieval Bulgarian scholar\nBULLET::::- Constantine (British saint), several obscure saints\n\nBULLET::::- Constantine, Algeria, the capital of Constantine Province\nBULLET::::- Constantine Province\nBULLET::::- Constantine (departement), in French Algeria\n\nBULLET::::- Constantine, Switzerland, a municipality in the canton of Vaud, Switzerland\n\nBULLET::::- Constantine, Cornwall, near Falmouth, United Kingdom\nBULLET::::- Constantine Bay, near Padstow, Cornwall, United Kingdom\nBULLET::::- Constantine College, York, a college of the University of York\n\nBULLET::::- Constantine, Michigan, a village in the United States\n\nBULLET:::